[2]
Date: Thu 4 Feb 2010
From: Merritt Clifton <anmlpepl@whidbey.com> [edited]


Based on the formula that I have developed since 1991 to estimate
feral cat populations, based on shelter intake and killing and kitten
adoption from the stray and feral population, the total New York City
feral cat population is probably about 36 000, mostly on Manhattan.

This is relatively low for a major metropolitan area, but the feral
cat density is greatly inhibited by the density of traffic and lack of
access for cats to much of the human habitat, that is, in high-rise
buildings.

This maybe could happen in some places, but I am skeptical that it
might be happening in Manhattan:

Firstly, there is no strain of rabies specific to cats, and cats are
not known to be a primary host or major vector of rabies. There are
far more cats at large than dogs, so with canine rabies officially
extinguished in the US, cats are found to be rabid more often, mostly
from tangling with raccoons, but they are seldom implicated in
transmission of cases.

Secondly, to my awareness the last known appearance of rabies among
cats in New York City was on Staten Island in June through August of
2006. Three rabid cats and 7 rabid raccoons turned up in the same
vicinity over a 5-month interval.

Thirdly, many and perhaps most feral cats in New York City have been
vaccinated and sterilized, and are under regular observation by
feeders. New York City has 3 of the oldest and largest feral cat
sterilization and vaccination projects in the US, and if any of the
cats they work with were rabid, alarms would soon sound.

Fourthly, I personally helped to trap, sterilize, vaccinate, and
return to their colonies 320 feral cats in northern Fairfield County,
Connecticut in 1991-1992 as part of a project that created a "rabies
barrier" of vaccinated feral cats between the raccoon population and
the owned but free-roaming cat population. The results of this project
were instrumental in popularizing neuter/return feral cat control
nationwide.

We were working in a raccoon rabies hot zone, and in fact, I picked up
3 confirmed rabid raccoons while trapping feral cats in the largest of
the 8 colonies we vaccinated and sterilized.

But we didn't find any rabid cats. Moreover, no rabid feral cats ever
were found in any of those colony areas. There was one rabid cat,
though: an unvaccinated pet cat, who got outside one night and fought
with a raccoon within a block of where I'd picked up one of the rabid
raccoons and about 6 feral cats.

What this experience suggested, basically, was that savvy feral cats
usually don't mess with raccoons, who are nest predators of kittens
and are big enough to knock a cat's eyeballs out with a swipe of the
paw, a type of injury we did see twice, in big toms who had obviously
engaged in boxing matches with raccoons that they lost, big time.
There were no bite wounds associated with those injuries.

Dim-witted, occasionally roaming pet cats do tangle with raccoons, and
are more likely to become infected by rabies.

Nationwide, there are about 6 to 7 million feral cats at large in
winter, and up to about 12-13 million in summer these days. This
compares to about 30 million free-roaming pet cats.

You'll see a lot of higher numbers thrown about, but those are
guesstimates from people who have not really done any serious
statistical research of the matter.

--
Merritt Clifton
Editor, Animal People
PO Box 960
Clinton, WA 98236
