[3]
Date: Thu 4 Feb 2010
From: Merritt Clifton <anmlpepl@whidbey.com> [edited]


Additional comments from Bryan Kortis <brykort@cs.com> of Neighborhood
Cats, the largest of the many NYC feral cat sterilization and
vaccination projects:

"There are probably tens of thousands of free-roaming cats in NYC, but
the vast majority are in the outer boroughs, not Manhattan where TNR
[trap/neuter/release] efforts have been intensive over the past 10
years -- though even before that, most of the cats were in Brooklyn,
Queens, Staten Island, and Bronx.

"I believe there have been a few cases of cat rabies since then, but
they're rare. Biggest concern is on Staten Island where rabies has
apparently spiked in the raccoon population. The theory that cats are
re-cycling raccoon rabies is not borne out by any facts I'm aware of,
that's just sheer speculation with no empirical foundation.

"We're tracking about 9000 to 10 000 cats and many more have been
TNR'ed who we're not tracking. Estimates are 10 000 free-roaming cats
were spayed/neutered in 2009 alone. By no means, however, are most of
NYC's free-roaming cats sterilized and vaccinated based on the
ever-growing demand for our services and the lack of decline in cat
intake at city shelters over the past several years."

---
Regarding the numbers Kortis provides, if 18 000 of the estimated 36
000 NYC feral cats are sterilized and vaccinated, the fecundity and
brief life span of most feral cats would combine to produce about 10
000 cats in need of sterilization each and every year. There would not
be a slowdown until the number already sterilized within the surviving
population topped 25 000.

Of the 10 000 sterilized and vaccinated per year, from 6000 to 9000
would be replacing mortality among the 18 000 who were already
sterilized and vaccinated, so the net gain would be 1000 to 4000
sterilized and vaccinated cats in the population.

I can't be more precise about the mortality rate, because while feral
cat mortality runs very high in most places, longevity increases after
cats are sterilized (because they roam less), and NYC, though it does
have some coyotes, foxes, and other predators of cats, has far fewer
than most US communities. Probably NYC has lower feral cat mortality
than most places, but how much lower?

We're actually talking about the same territory regarding discussion
of Manhattan, Brooklyn, Queens and the Bronx. Bryan, who lives there,
correctly cites the borough; when I wrote "mostly on Manhattan," I
meant the contiguous area of the city, exclusive of Staten Island, and
forgot about the rivers that separate Manhattan from those boroughs
that don't have "island" in their names.

--
Merritt Clifton
Editor, Animal People
PO Box 960
Clinton, WA 98236
USA
